{{Infobox person |name = Eric Halsall |image = |image_size = |alt = |caption = |birth_name = |birth_date = {{Birth date|1920|3|18|df=y}} |birth_place = {{Flagicon|UK}}[[Burnley]], [[Lancashire]], [[England]], [[UK]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|1996|10|21|1920|3|18|df=y}} |death_place = {{Flagicon|UK}}[[Burnley]], [[Lancashire]], [[England]], [[UK]] |death_cause = |resting_place = |resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} --> |nationality = |other_names = |known_for = |education = |alma_mater = |occupation = [[Author]], [[television presenter]] |years_active = |home_town = |networth = |boards = |religion = |spouse = |children = |parents = |relations = |awards = |signature = |website = |footnotes = }}
'''Eric Halsall''' (18 March 1920 &ndash; 21 October 1996) was an [[England|English]] [[wikt:countryman|countryman]], [[author]] and [[television presenter]]. Best known for his fourteen-year run as a commentator on [[BBC]] TV series ''[[One Man and His Dog]]''.
==Early life== Halsall was born and brought up in [[Burnley]], [[Lancashire]], attending [[Burnley Grammar School]].<ref>The Author's & writer's who's who [https://books.google.com/books?ei=I17wTPvgDIexhQf5ztH6Cw&ct=result&id=vSUNAAAAIAAJ&dq=Eric+Halsall+Burnley+Grammar&q=Eric+Halsall Snippet at Google Books] Accessed 2010</ref> He was a keen footballer and had a trial at [[Burnley F.C.]]. Turned down by the [[RAF]], he joined the [[Burnley Express]], initially in advertising and then as a writer. He married Rita Greenwood in 1942.
==Career== Halsall worked from the 1950s until 1985 as a farms manager for the [[National Coal Board]]. However he was best known as presenter of the long-running TV series ''[[One Man and His Dog]]'', in which he commentated on [[sheepdog trial]]s for 14 years from 1975 to 1989. He was also the course director for the series, in charge of laying out the trial fields.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituaries-eric-halsall-1360034.html The Independent - Obituaries] Accessed 2010</ref>
Halsall also served for 21 years as a director of the [[International Sheep Dog Society]], and was a winner of its Wilkinson Sword Trophy Award.
==Later life== Halsall lived in the [[Cliviger]] area, close to Burnley. He was president of the Burnley branch of [[the Guide Dogs for the Blind Association]].<ref>[http://www.thisislancashire.co.uk/archive/1996/10/23/Lancashire+Archive/6194945.Eric_Halsall_of_TV_s__One_Man_and_his_Dog__dies/ This is Lancashire - news archive] Accessed 2010</ref>
